<font color="#FF0000">COMMENTS</font><br>
<tt>Sun Sep 14 16:09:37 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I find it interesting that the Vietnam War has been disected into a million or so pieces, examined in the light of about every point of view, and no one still has any answers. I think it is because there are no definitive answers on any of it, except that it was pretty much a very short round, no matter how you look at it.<br><br>
I really wanted absolutely nothing to do with the Vietnamese people in country after some guys in the 8/6 mess hall got blown away with a few chicom frags tied to the back of mess hall trays in the racks. One of the worst &quot;aiding the enemy&quot; practices was allowing &quot;cleared&quot; locals to work in the FSB's and base camps. If they weren't pacing off the coordinates to everything, they were up to other mischief. We have the pentagon panty sqad to thank for that.<br><br>
The children were true victims. They had no choice. They were there and were stuck with everything that happened. The eyes still haunt me.<br><br>
I appreciate Cook's view on the CO activities in 'Nam, especially with the bags of rice, and the covert medical attention to wounded gooks, but we cannot lose sight of the fact that it it was as much of a two faced war for the Vietnamese people as it was for us. Anything and everything did happen. We also did a lot to ourselves with those &quot;no fire zones&quot; around villes. I also never saw an intel target that ment anything. It was more of a lottery with coordinates. When you drop operational plans out of a loach and go ahead with the operation anyway, the hot LZ you get should be no surprise. I saw it happen.<br><br>
Speaking of leftist propaganda, I was pretty disgusted with what was going on at home when I was in country. However, the US military had their own brand of propaganda for the troops that was as much of a distortion of reality as anything I have ever seen. Jane Fonda and Robert MacNamara (and a few others) should have been locked up in the same cage and hung up over the Reflecting Pool for public ridicule. Skunks all have the same stripes. Here, kitty, kitty.<br><br>
Cook, you should be proud that the 'Nam Vet Marines I deal with today are about the squarest bunch of guys I have ever seen. One in particular, though, is still haunted by the acts of those who were not as well disciplined. I have every faith that Marines were not behind some of the breaches of conduct for which I have heard stories, but stuff did happen, and it was not pretty. But what else is new when on the knife's edge and berserk. This society has to learn that it cannot judge war conduct as it does civilian conduct. Personally, I feel that all the after the fact self flagellation over &quot;incidents&quot; was disgusting, and those punished were scapegoats for reasons of political guilt by those who were behind us being there in the first place.<br><br>
I was never a very religous person, but I was far less of one after I returned from 'Nam. It seems that I lost something over there. Actually, I lost myself, and a lot more as I have come to learn. At least I now have the advantage of putting it all back together better than it was before. A real second chance. To whom do I look to thank for that? I wonder....   <br><br>
Wow, off the soap box. I guess I have a lot on my mind. But then again, I guess everyone does.<br><br>
 <br><br>

